<script>
    import Preview from "$lib/components/Preview.svelte"
</script>

Walk into a restaurant. The specials board yells at you. Walk into a store. The sale sign practically tackles you. Good UI does the same: it grabs your attention and shouts, "LOOK HERE FIRST!" That's hierarchy.

## Hierarchy: Not Just for Royalty

Every screen gets read in some order. Hierarchy is how you control that order. You decide what gets seen first, second, and "oh, you're still here?"

The goal isn't to make everything visible. It's to make the _right_ things visible.

## The Three Tiers of UI Fame

- **Primary:** The star of your screen. One per page, please.
- **Secondary:** The backup dancers. Still important, but not stealing the spotlight.
- **Tertiary:** The roadies. Metadata, links, legal text, and "P.S." stuff.

If you have three primaries, you have zero primaries. (Math checks out.)

**The Squint Test:** Squint until your screen blurs (or just take off your glasses). What stands out? That's your primary. If everything pops, you've got a problem.

## Hierarchy in the Wild (A UI Safari)

Here's a screen where everything is the same size and weight. The user has to read _everything_ to figure out what matters. (They won't.)

<Preview>
  <div class="p-6 bg-white font-sans max-w-sm border rounded-lg space-y-2">
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700">Welcome back, Jordan</p>
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700">Your plan: Pro</p>
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700">Storage used: 4.2 GB of 10 GB</p>
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700">Last login: 2 days ago</p>
    <button class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 border border-gray-400 px-3 py-1 rounded w-full">Upgrade plan</button>
    <button class="text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 border border-gray-400 px-3 py-1 rounded w-full">Manage storage</button>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Nothing stands out. User has to work to find importance. (Also, labels everywhere! Well roast those in a minute.)</p>
  </div>
</Preview>

Now, same info, but with clear tiers. The primary action is unmistakable. Secondary info is chill. Tertiary stuff is there if you care.

<Preview>
  <div class="p-6 bg-white font-sans max-w-sm border rounded-lg shadow-sm space-y-4">
    <div>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900">4.2 GB used</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-0.5">of 10 GB — 58% remaining</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-full h-2 w-full overflow-hidden">
      <div class="bg-blue-500 h-full rounded-full" style="width: 42%"></div>
    </div>
    <button class="bg-blue-600 text-white font-semibold text-sm px-4 py-2.5 rounded-md w-full">
      Upgrade for more storage
    </button>
    <div class="flex justify-between text-xs text-gray-400">
      <span>Pro plan</span>
      <span>Last login 2 days ago</span>
    </div>
  </div>
