The storage number is the story, big and bold. The context is secondary. The progress bar is a visual cue. The CTA gets the spotlight. The plan and login date are there, but quiet.

### Emphasize by De-Emphasizing (The Music Producer's Secret)

Fun fact: I dabble in music production. (Yes, I'm that cool.) Sometimes, making something stand out isn't about cranking the volume, it's about turning everything else down. Same with UI. Let's see:

<Preview> 
  <div class="flex gap-4 m-4">
    <div class="p-4 border rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-lg">Basic</h3> 
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold">$9</p> 
    </div> 
    <div class="p-4 border rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-lg">Pro</h3> 
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold">$19</p>
    </div> 
    <div class="p-4 border rounded-lg"> 
      <h3 class="font-bold text-lg">Enterprise</h3> 
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold">$49</p>
    </div>
  </div> 
</Preview>

Now, let's tone down the non-primary steps:

<Preview>
  <div class="flex gap-4 m-4">
      <div class="p-4 border rounded-lg opacity-60">
      <h3 class="font-medium text-lg text-neutral-600">Basic</h3>
      <p class="text-2xl font-medium text-neutral-600">$9</p>
    </div> 
    <div class="p-6 border-2 border-pink-500 rounded-xl shadow-lg">
      <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-pink-500">Pro</h3>
      <p class="text-3xl font-bold">$19</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-4 border rounded-lg opacity-60">
      <h3 class="font-medium text-lg text-neutral-600">Enterprise</h3>
      <p class="text-2xl font-medium text-neutral-600">$49</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Preview>

## Not Everything Needs a Label (The Apple Store Fallacy)

It's tempting to label everything, like a grocery store. But sometimes, labels just get in the way.

<Preview>
  <div class="shadow-lg flex flex-col items-center rounded-md p-12 mx-auto w-fit">
    <img src="https://www.publicdomainpictures.net/pictures/70000/velka/red-apple-white-background.jpg" class="w-32 h-24" />
    <div>
      <p><span class="font-bold">Name:</span> Apples</p>
      <p><span class="font-bold">Price:</span> $13 USD / kg</p>
      <p><span class="font-bold">Provider:</span> The House of Apple Trees</p>
      <button class="mt-4 px-3 py-1 bg-red-400 rounded">Add to Cart</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</Preview>

What if we just didn't?

<Preview>
  <div class="shadow-lg flex flex-col items-center rounded-md p-12 mx-auto w-fit">
    <img src="https://www.publicdomainpictures.net/pictures/70000/velka/red-apple-white-background.jpg" class="w-32 h-24" />
    <div>
      <p class="text-center font-black text-xl">Apples</p>
      <p class="font-medium">$13 USD / kg</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-500 text-sm">From The House of Apple Trees</p>
      <button class="mt-4 px-3 py-1 bg-red-400 rounded">Add to Cart</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</Preview>

Icons work too. (Just don't overdo it.)

### Labels as Support

Sometimes, labels are helpful for hierarchy. Like when you want to show off your monthly sales:

<Preview>
  <div class="shadow-lg bg-neutral-800 flex flex-col text-neutral-200 rounded-md mx-auto w-fit">
    <div class="flex gap-4 items-center py-4 px-12">
